data.content:
## Thread.Abort Migration to .NET 8

Your code has **three** APIs that don't work in modern .NET:

| API | Problem in .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (`SYSLIB0006`) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — dead code |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

### Patterns identified

1. **Cancellable work loop** — `while (_running)` loop in `ProcessLoop`
2. **ThreadAbortException as control flow** — catch block does rollback cleanup
3. **Thread.ResetAbort to continue** — keeps the thread alive for the next iteration
4. **Thread.Abort as force-stop** — `Stop()` uses it when graceful shutdown fails

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;

        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can wake up
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop (replaces ResetAbort + loop continuation)
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts == null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait for the worker to finish (replaces Thread.Sleep + Abort)
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### What changed and why

**`volatile bool _running` → `CancellationTokenSource`**
The token can interrupt blocking calls (`WaitOne`, `Task.Delay`, async I/O). A bool can only be checked between iterations — if `GetNextItem()` blocks, the old code hangs until `Abort` forces it.

**`Thread.Abort()` → `_cts.Cancel()`**
Cooperative cancellation. Any method holding the token will see the request and throw `OperationCanceledException` at its next checkpoint.

**`catch (ThreadAbortException)` → `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (...)`**
The `when` filter ensures you only catch cancellation you initiated — not unrelated `OperationCanceledException` from other sources.

**`Thread.ResetAbort()` → removed**
`ResetAbort` prevented rethrow so the loop could continue. In cooperative cancellation, you control the flow explicitly: `break` to exit, or just continue the loop for the next item.

**`Thread.Sleep(2000)` → `_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2))`**
`Join` actually waits for the thread to finish rather than sleeping a fixed duration and hoping.

### Critical: You must update `GetNextItem`

The original comment says `GetNextItem()` "may block." This is the **most important** change — if it doesn't accept a `CancellationToken`, cancellation stalls until the blocking call returns on its own:

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks indefinitely, can't be interrupted
private WorkItem GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // BlockingCollection.Take()
}

// AFTER — wakes up immediately on cancellation
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If `GetNextItem` uses `Thread.Sleep`, `WaitHandle.WaitOne`, or synchronous I/O:

```csharp
// Replace Thread.Sleep with cancellation-aware wait
Thread.Sleep(5000);              // ❌ not interruptible
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(5000);  // ✅ wakes on cancel

// Replace WaitOne with cancellation-aware overload
handle.WaitOne();                                        // ❌
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { handle, token.WaitHandle });  // ✅
```

### Common pitfalls

| Pitfall | Impact |
|---|---|
| Not passing `CancellationToken` through the full call chain | Cancellation silently stalls — `Cancel()` fires but nothing responds |
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | Leaks timers and registered callbacks |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` and swallowing it | Hides cancellation from callers — let it propagate except at top-level orchestration |
| Assuming cancellation is immediate | It only fires at the next checkpoint — large work items delay it |
| Using `Thread.Interrupt` as a substitute | Also obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9), and only works on `WaitSleepJoin` state threads |

If `ProcessItem` is long-running, add checkpoints inside it:

```csharp
private void ProcessItem(WorkItem item, CancellationToken token)
{
    foreach (var step in item.Steps)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        ExecuteStep(step);
    }
}
```
